Ok, I changed a little bit the method:
@@@ ruby # Destroy +records+ and remove from this association calling +before_remove+ # and +after_remove+ callbacks. # # Note this method will always remove records from database ignoring the # +:dependent+ option. def destroy(*records) records = flatten_deeper(records) records.each { |record| raise_on_type_mismatch(record) }
transaction do records.each { |record| callback(:before_remove, record) }
old_records = records.reject { |r| r.new_record? } old_records.each { |record| record.destroy }
records.each do |record| callback(:after_remove, record) end end
load_target end @@@
And also refactored `destroy_all`: @@@ ruby def destroy_all destroy(self) reset_target! end @@@
Now the code Inside `AutosaveAssociation` is clean: @@@ ruby association.destroy(record) @@@
Of course all tests pass, and there aren't repetitions about callbacks evaluation. I think it's a nice solution now :)
I attach the new version of the patch.
